## The problem

```text
Pod-1 (server-1) — user uploads profile.jpg → stored at /var/uploads/profile.jpg
Pod-2 (server-2) — user requests profile.jpg → FileNotFoundException!

Each pod has its own disk. Uploads on pod-1 don't exist on pod-2.
Also: no redundancy, no CDN, files lost if server restarts.
```

---

## The fix: S3/MinIO for shared, distributed storage

```text
[Client]
  ↓  POST /api/uploads/presign  (get a presigned URL)
[Your API] → generates presigned URL → returns to client
  ↓  PUT directly to S3 URL  (file goes to S3, not your API!)
[S3/MinIO] → stores file, client gets 200
  ↓  POST /api/uploads/confirm  (client tells your API "upload done")
[Your API] → validates, saves metadata to DB, returns file URL
```

**Why presigned URLs?** File upload goes DIRECTLY from client to S3 — your API servers don't handle file bytes, no memory/bandwidth pressure.

---

## Step 1: MinIO client setup (works the same for AWS S3)

```xml
<dependency>
  <groupId>io.minio</groupId>
  <artifactId>minio</artifactId>
  <version>8.5.7</version>
</dependency>
```

```java
@Configuration
public class StorageConfig {

    @Value("${storage.endpoint}")
    private String endpoint;  // https://s3.amazonaws.com or http://minio:9000

    @Value("${storage.access-key}")
    private String accessKey;

    @Value("${storage.secret-key}")
    private String secretKey;

    @Bean
    public MinioClient minioClient() {
        return MinioClient.builder()
            .endpoint(endpoint)
            .credentials(accessKey, secretKey)
            .build();
    }
}
```

---

## Step 2: Presigned upload URL

```java
@Service
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class FileStorageService {

    private final MinioClient minio;

    private static final long MAX_FILE_SIZE_BYTES = 50 * 1024 * 1024L; // 50MB
    private static final Set<String> ALLOWED_CONTENT_TYPES = Set.of(
        "image/jpeg", "image/png", "image/webp",
        "application/pdf", "video/mp4"
    );

    public PresignedUploadResponse generateUploadUrl(
            Long userId, String filename, String contentType, long fileSizeBytes) {

        // Validate before generating URL
        if (fileSizeBytes > MAX_FILE_SIZE_BYTES) {
            throw new FileTooLargeException("Max 50MB allowed");
        }
        if (!ALLOWED_CONTENT_TYPES.contains(contentType)) {
            throw new InvalidFileTypeException("Unsupported file type: " + contentType);
        }

        // Generate unique storage key (prevent path traversal attacks)
        String ext = filename.substring(filename.lastIndexOf('.'));
        String objectKey = String.format("users/%d/uploads/%s%s",
            userId, UUID.randomUUID(), ext);

        try {
            // Generate presigned PUT URL valid for 15 minutes
            Map<String, String> conditions = new HashMap<>();
            conditions.put("content-type", contentType);

            String presignedUrl = minio.getPresignedObjectUrl(
                GetPresignedObjectUrlArgs.builder()
                    .method(Method.PUT)
                    .bucket("user-uploads")
                    .object(objectKey)
                    .expiry(15, TimeUnit.MINUTES)
                    .extraQueryParams(conditions)
                    .build());

            // Save pending upload to DB for confirmation
            pendingUploadRepo.save(PendingUpload.builder()
                .userId(userId)
                .objectKey(objectKey)
                .contentType(contentType)
                .status(UploadStatus.PENDING)
                .expiresAt(Instant.now().plusSeconds(900))
                .build());

            return new PresignedUploadResponse(presignedUrl, objectKey);

        } catch (MinioException e) {
            throw new StorageException("Failed to generate upload URL", e);
        }
    }

    // Called after client finishes PUT to S3
    public FileMetadata confirmUpload(Long userId, String objectKey) {
        PendingUpload pending = pendingUploadRepo
            .findByUserIdAndObjectKeyAndStatus(userId, objectKey, UploadStatus.PENDING)
            .orElseThrow(() -> new InvalidUploadException("Unknown or expired upload"));

        // Verify file actually exists in S3
        try {
            StatObjectResponse stat = minio.statObject(
                StatObjectArgs.builder()
                    .bucket("user-uploads")
                    .object(objectKey)
                    .build());

            // Save permanent metadata
            FileMetadata meta = FileMetadata.builder()
                .userId(userId)
                .objectKey(objectKey)
                .contentType(stat.contentType())
                .sizeBytes(stat.size())
                .status(FileStatus.ACTIVE)
                .build();
            fileMetadataRepo.save(meta);

            pending.setStatus(UploadStatus.CONFIRMED);
            pendingUploadRepo.save(pending);

            log.info("Upload confirmed: {} ({} bytes)", objectKey, stat.size());
            return meta;

        } catch (MinioException e) {
            throw new StorageException("File not found in storage after upload", e);
        }
    }
}
```

---

## Step 3: Presigned download URL (don't expose S3 directly)

```java
public String generateDownloadUrl(Long userId, String objectKey, int expiryMinutes) {
    // Verify user owns this file
    FileMetadata meta = fileMetadataRepo
        .findByObjectKey(objectKey)
        .orElseThrow(() -> new FileNotFoundException(objectKey));

    if (!meta.getUserId().equals(userId)) {
        throw new AccessDeniedException("Access denied to file: " + objectKey);
    }

    try {
        return minio.getPresignedObjectUrl(
            GetPresignedObjectUrlArgs.builder()
                .method(Method.GET)
                .bucket("user-uploads")
                .object(objectKey)
                .expiry(expiryMinutes, TimeUnit.MINUTES)
                .build());
    } catch (MinioException e) {
        throw new StorageException("Failed to generate download URL", e);
    }
}
```

**Expected presigned URL (for client to PUT to):**
```text
https://s3.amazonaws.com/user-uploads/users/123/uploads/uuid-abc.jpg
  ?X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256
  &X-Amz-Credential=AKIAIOSFODNN7EXAMPLE...
  &X-Amz-Expires=900
  &X-Amz-Signature=fe5f80...

Client does: PUT <presigned-url> with file content in body
Result: file stored in S3, your server never saw the file bytes
```

---

## Large file uploads: Multipart

For files > 5MB, use multipart upload — resilient to network interruptions:

```bash
# AWS CLI example showing multipart upload
# Step 1: initiate
aws s3api create-multipart-upload --bucket user-uploads --key large-video.mp4
# Returns: { "UploadId": "VXBsb2FkIElEIGZvciA2aWWpbmcncyBteS1tb3ZpZS5tMnRzIHVwbG9hZA" }

# Step 2: upload parts (each must be >= 5MB except the last)
aws s3api upload-part --bucket user-uploads --key large-video.mp4 \
  --part-number 1 --body part1.mp4 --upload-id <UploadId>
# Returns: { "ETag": "\"d8c2eafd90c266e19ab9dcacc479f8af\"" }

# Step 3: complete (combine parts)
aws s3api complete-multipart-upload --bucket user-uploads --key large-video.mp4 \
  --multipart-upload '{"Parts":[{"PartNumber":1,"ETag":"..."}]}' \
  --upload-id <UploadId>
```

**SDK in Java:**
```java
// MinIO automatically does multipart for objects > 5MB
minio.uploadObject(UploadObjectArgs.builder()
    .bucket("user-uploads")
    .object(objectKey)
    .filename(localFilePath)  // MinIO splits into parts automatically
    .contentType(contentType)
    .build());
```

---

## Your interview answer

> "Local disk storage breaks horizontal scaling — files only exist on the pod that received the upload. I migrated to S3 using presigned URLs: the API generates a time-limited PUT URL, the client uploads directly to S3 (so no file bytes through our servers), and then calls a /confirm endpoint. The API verifies the file exists in S3, validates content type and size, and saves metadata to PostgreSQL. Downloads use presigned GET URLs — protected by our authorization check before generating. For files over 5MB, S3's multipart upload handles interruptions gracefully."

followUps.answer:
**Layer 1 — Validate before generating presigned URL:**
```java
// In the /presign endpoint
if (fileSizeBytes > MAX_SIZE) throw new FileTooLargeException();
if (!ALLOWED_TYPES.contains(contentType)) throw new InvalidFileTypeException();
// Note: client-provided content-type and size are untrustworthy — validate after upload too
```

**Layer 2 — S3 bucket policy (enforced by S3, not bypassable):**
```json
// Bucket lifecycle policy: reject files > 50MB at S3 level
{
  "Conditions": [
    ["content-length-range", 1, 52428800]
  ]
}
// Include in presigned URL conditions
```

**Layer 3 — Post-upload validation in /confirm:**
```java
public FileMetadata confirmUpload(String objectKey) {
    StatObjectResponse stat = minio.statObject(...);

    // Re-validate content-type from S3 (not client-claimed)
    if (!ALLOWED_TYPES.contains(stat.contentType())) {
        minio.removeObject(RemoveObjectArgs.builder().bucket("user-uploads").object(objectKey).build());
        throw new InvalidFileTypeException("File rejected: " + stat.contentType());
    }

    // Check magic bytes for images (prevent .exe renamed to .jpg)
    InputStream stream = minio.getObject(GetObjectArgs.builder().bucket("user-uploads").object(objectKey).build());
    byte[] header = stream.readNBytes(8);
    if (!isValidImageHeader(header, stat.contentType())) {
        minio.removeObject(...); // delete the fake file
        throw new InvalidFileTypeException("File content does not match declared type");
    }
}

// Check magic bytes
private boolean isValidImageHeader(byte[] bytes, String contentType) {
    return switch (contentType) {
        case "image/jpeg" -> bytes[0] == (byte)0xFF && bytes[1] == (byte)0xD8;
        case "image/png"  -> bytes[0] == (byte)0x89 && bytes[1] == 'P' && bytes[2] == 'N' && bytes[3] == 'G';
        default -> false;
    };
}
```

**Layer 4 — Async virus scan (for documents):**
```java
@KafkaListener(topics = "file.uploaded")
public void scanForViruses(FileUploadedEvent event) {
    // ClamAV integration
    boolean isMalicious = clamAVClient.scan(event.getObjectKey());
    if (isMalicious) {
        minio.removeObject(...);
        fileMetadataRepo.updateStatus(event.getObjectKey(), FileStatus.QUARANTINED);
        alertSecurityTeam(event);
    }
}
```

**Golden rule**: S3/MinIO stores the BYTES. Your PostgreSQL stores the METADATA and business logic.

**What stays in S3:**
- The actual file bytes
- Basic headers (Content-Type, Content-Length)
- S3 system metadata (ETag, last modified)

**What you store in PostgreSQL:**
```sql
CREATE TABLE file_metadata (
    id          UUID PRIMARY KEY DEFAULT gen_random_uuid(),
    user_id     BIGINT NOT NULL REFERENCES users(id),
    object_key  TEXT   NOT NULL UNIQUE,  -- S3 key: users/123/uploads/uuid.jpg
    filename    TEXT   NOT NULL,         -- original filename from user
    content_type VARCHAR(100) NOT NULL,
    size_bytes  BIGINT NOT NULL,
    status      VARCHAR(20) DEFAULT 'ACTIVE',  -- ACTIVE, DELETED, QUARANTINED
    is_public   BOOLEAN DEFAULT FALSE,
    created_at  TIMESTAMPTZ DEFAULT NOW(),
    deleted_at  TIMESTAMPTZ             -- soft delete
);
```

**Why NOT just use S3 as your source of truth:**
```text
S3 listing (list all files for user) → eventual consistency, slow, can't filter
DB query (SELECT * FROM file_metadata WHERE user_id = 123) → fast, consistent, filterable

Also:
- S3 doesn't know which user owns which file (it's just a key)
- S3 can't enforce your soft-delete business rules
- S3 listing is expensive ($0.005 per 1000 requests)
```

**Soft delete pattern:**
```java
public void deleteFile(Long userId, UUID fileId) {
    FileMetadata meta = fileMetadataRepo.findByIdAndUserId(fileId, userId).orElseThrow();

    // Soft delete in DB immediately (file appears deleted to user)
    meta.setStatus(FileStatus.DELETED);
    meta.setDeletedAt(Instant.now());
    fileMetadataRepo.save(meta);

    // Physical S3 deletion runs async (cheaper, batched)
    // Scheduled job deletes S3 objects older than 7 days with status=DELETED
}

@Scheduled(cron = "0 0 3 * * *")
public void cleanupDeletedFiles() {
    List<FileMetadata> toDelete = fileMetadataRepo
        .findByStatusAndDeletedAtBefore(FileStatus.DELETED, Instant.now().minus(7, DAYS));
    for (FileMetadata meta : toDelete) {
        minio.removeObject(...);
        fileMetadataRepo.delete(meta);
    }
}
```

