followUps.answer:
By default, `@Scheduled` fires again even if the previous run is still going. This can cause:
1. Two instances of the same job running simultaneously (race condition)
2. Resource exhaustion (DB connections, memory)

**Fix 1 — ShedLock with lockAtLeastFor:**
```java
@SchedulerLock(
    name = "report-generator",
    lockAtMostFor  = "25m",  // auto-release if crash
    lockAtLeastFor = "20m"   // hold lock for 20 min minimum
)
@Scheduled(fixedRate = 10 * 60 * 1000)  // every 10 minutes
public void generateReports() { ... }
// If job takes 15 min, lockAtLeastFor=20m means next fire at 10min is skipped
```

**Fix 2 — `@Scheduled(fixedDelay)` instead of `fixedRate`:**
```java
// fixedRate: fires every 10 min regardless of how long last run took
@Scheduled(fixedRate = 10 * 60 * 1000)
void badJob() { ... }

// fixedDelay: waits 10 min AFTER the previous run COMPLETES
@Scheduled(fixedDelay = 10 * 60 * 1000)
void goodJob() { ... }
// If job takes 15 min, next run starts at 15+10=25 min — no overlap possible
```

**Fix 3 — Atomic flag to skip if already running:**
```java
private final AtomicBoolean isRunning = new AtomicBoolean(false);

@Scheduled(fixedRate = 60000)
public void job() {
    if (!isRunning.compareAndSet(false, true)) {
        log.info("Job still running — skipping this fire");
        return;
    }
    try {
        doWork();
    } finally {
        isRunning.set(false);
    }
}
```

Note: the AtomicBoolean approach only works within a SINGLE JVM. Across multiple instances, use ShedLock.

