## The multi-pod problem — and the Redis Pub/Sub fix

```text
Problem:
  User A is connected to Pod-1 WebSocket session.
  Order status update event is consumed by Pod-2's Kafka consumer.
  Pod-2 calls messagingTemplate.convertAndSendToUser("userA", ...)
  But User A's WebSocket session is on Pod-1, not Pod-2!
  → Message is lost.
```

```java
// Fix: Use Redis as message broker (replaces in-memory SimpleBroker)
@Configuration
@EnableWebSocketMessageBroker
public class WebSocketConfig implements WebSocketMessageBrokerConfigurer {

    @Override
    public void configureMessageBroker(MessageBrokerRegistry registry) {
        // Use Redis-backed STOMP broker instead of in-memory
        registry.enableStompBrokerRelay("/topic", "/queue")
            .setRelayHost("redis")
            .setRelayPort(6379)
            .setClientLogin("guest")
            .setClientPasscode("guest");
        // Now ALL pods share the same message broker — pod-2 can deliver to pod-1's sessions
    }
}
```

**With Redis broker:**
```text
Pod-2 Kafka consumer: messagingTemplate.convertAndSendToUser("userA", "/queue/order-updates", msg)
  → publishes to Redis channel: /user/userA/queue/order-updates
  → Redis broadcasts to all subscribers
  → Pod-1 is subscribed → delivers to UserA's WebSocket session
  → User sees update in real-time!
```

